{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627443"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:48:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:48:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17118"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17118"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.89,0,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9808"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111361"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9808"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17118"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93491"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5026"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45233"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111361"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with palpitations. Her heart rate is 130/min and blood pressure is 145/85 mmHg. An electrocardiogram shows atrial fibrillation with a rapid ventricular response. She is started on metoprolol for rate control.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the cellular mechanism by which this medication reduces sinoatrial node automaticity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits voltage-gated sodium channel activation","Reduces cyclic AMP-mediated channel phosphorylation","Enhances acetylcholine release from vagal terminals","Directly blocks L-type calcium channels","Increases potassium channel conductance"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBeta-1 selective blockers such as metoprolol reduce sinoatrial node automaticity by \u003Cstrong\u003Ereducing cyclic AMP-mediated channel phosphorylation\u003C/strong\u003E. Blocking beta-1 receptors decreases adenylyl cyclase activity and cyclic AMP production, lowering protein kinase A activity. This reduces phosphorylation and activation of hyperpolarisation-activated cyclic nucleotide-gated channels and L-type calcium channels, flattening phase 4 depolarisation in pacemaker cells and slowing heart rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits voltage-gated sodium channel activation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as this is the mechanism of class 1 antiarrhythmic medications and not beta blockers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances acetylcholine release from vagal terminals\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, because beta blockers act by antagonising adrenergic receptors rather than enhancing parasympathetic neurotransmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly blocks L-type calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E describes the action of class 4 antiarrhythmic medications; beta blockers decrease calcium channel activity indirectly via reduced phosphorylation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases potassium channel conductance\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as beta blockers do not directly increase potassium currents, although other antiarrhythmics act via potassium channels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn atrial fibrillation, beta blockers slow atrioventricular nodal conduction and reduce ventricular rate by decreasing sympathetic drive and pacemaker current activity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beta blockers reduce the slope of phase 4 depolarisation in pacemaker cells by decreasing cyclic AMP-mediated activation of hyperpolarisation-activated cyclic nucleotide-gated channels.","Beta-1 selective blockers preferentially reduce sinoatrial node automaticity and atrioventricular conduction without significantly affecting bronchial smooth muscle.","The antiarrhythmic effect of beta blockers is most pronounced in catecholamine-driven arrhythmias where sympathetic tone plays a major role."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93491"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17118"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93491"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T11:42:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T11:43:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9808"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111361"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.